==English==
===Etymology===
Via Persian, from Arabic {{ARchar|[[غزل]]}} (''gházal'', ‘love poetry’), from {{ARchar|[[غزل]]}} (''gházala'' ‘to spin,’ ‘to display amourous behavior’) (but popularly associated with {{ARchar|[[غزال]]}} ''ghazāl'' ‘[[gazelle]]’).

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'gæzæl/, ''foreign'' /ʕazal/}}

===Noun===
'''ghazal''' (''plural:'' '''ghazals''')

# a poetic form mostly used for love poetry in Turkish, Urdu, Arabic, and especially Persian.
#:*'''2001''': Indeed, this is a realm where colors harmoniously recite magnificent '''ghazals''' to each other, where time stops, where the Devil never appears. — Orhan Pamuk, ''My Name Is Red'', tr. Erdağ M. Göknar

